children.text: The noggings installed between the wall studs for the horizontal joins within the plywood bracing sheets within the walls have not been installed flush with the faces of the studs, nor are they of the same size as the top and bottom plates.

The plywood sheet bracing installation is a vital structural member in the dwelling. It stops the house from moving when racking forces, such as wind, are applied to a dwelling. The relevant Australian Standard, AS 1684 Residential timber-framed construction, clause 6.2.1.5 Nogging, states that

‘Where required to provide fixing or support to cladding or lining or for joining bracing sheets at horizontal joints, noggings shall be installed flush with one face of the stud; and where required to permit joining bracing sheets at horizontal joints, noggings shall be the same size as the top and bottom plate required for that bracing wall’ .
The present noggings will need to be replaced with ones that are of the correct size and that are installed flush with the faces of the studs they are fixed between.
